  "prompt": "English Grammar: Which is more Grammatically Correct - \"I wish I was there\" OR \"I wish I were there\"?",
  "response": "\"I wish I were there\" is more grammatically correct. This usage applies the subjunctive mood, which is used to express hypotheticals, wishes, or situations that are contrary to fact. In this case, \"were\" indicates that the speaker is expressing a wish about a situation that is not currently true. \n\nWhile \"I wish I was there\" is commonly heard in everyday conversation and is accepted in informal contexts, standard English grammar prefers \"were\" for such constructions.",
